# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phase-transitions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] In thermodynamics, a **critical point** (or **critical state**) is the end point of a phase equilibrium curve.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] One example is the liquid–vapor critical point, the end point of the pressure–temperature curve that designates conditions under which a liquid and its vapor can coexist.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] At higher temperatures, the gas comes into a supercritical phase, and so cannot be liquefied by pressure alone.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] At the critical point, defined by a *critical temperature* *T*c and a *critical pressure* *p*c, phase boundaries vanish.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] Other examples include the liquid–liquid critical points in mixtures, and the ferromagnet–paramagnet transition (Curie temperature) in the absence of an external magnetic field.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The liquid–vapor critical point was the first critical point to be discovered, and it remains the best known and most studied one.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The figure shows the schematic *P-T* diagram of a *pure substance* (as opposed to mixtures, which have additional state variables and richer phase diagrams, discussed below).
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The commonly known phases *solid*, *liquid* and *vapor* are separated by phase boundaries, i.e. pressure–temperature combinations where two phases can coexist.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] At the triple point, all three phases can coexist.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] However, the liquid–vapor boundary terminates in an endpoint at some *critical temperature* *T*c and *critical pressure* *p*c.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] In the *vicinity* of the critical point, the physical properties of the liquid and the vapor change dramatically, with both phases becoming even more similar.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] For instance, liquid water under normal conditions is nearly incompressible, has a low thermal expansion coefficient, has a high dielectric constant, and is an excellent solvent for electrolytes.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] Near the critical point, all these properties change into the exact opposite: water becomes compressible, expandable, a poor dielectric, a bad solvent for electrolytes, and mixes more readily with nonpolar gases and organic molecules.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The existence of a critical point was first discovered by Charles Cagniard de la Tour in 1822 and named by Dmitri Mendeleev in 1860 and Thomas Andrews in 1869.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] Cagniard showed that CO2 could be liquefied at 31 °C at a pressure of 73 atm, but not at a slightly higher temperature, even under pressures as high as 3000 atm.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] However, the van der Waals equation, based on a mean-field theory, does not hold near the critical point.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] In particular, it predicts wrong scaling laws.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The principle of corresponding states indicates that substances at equal reduced pressures and temperatures have equal reduced volumes.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] This relationship is approximately true for many substances, but becomes increasingly inaccurate for large values of *p*r.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] For some gases, there is an additional correction factor, called *Newton's correction*, added to the critical temperature and critical pressure calculated in this manner.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] These are empirically derived values and vary with the pressure range of interest.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] The liquid–liquid critical point of a solution, which occurs at the *critical solution temperature*, occurs at the limit of the two-phase region of the phase diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] In other words, it is the point at which an infinitesimal change in some thermodynamic variable (such as temperature or pressure) leads to separation of the mixture into two distinct liquid phases, as shown in the polymer–solvent phase diagram to the right.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] Two types of liquid–liquid critical points are the upper critical solution temperature (UCST), which is the hottest point at which cooling induces phase separation, and the lower critical solution temperature (LCST), which is the coldest point at which heating induces phase separation.
[src:phase-transitions/critical-point-thermodynamics] From a theoretical standpoint, the liquid–liquid critical point represents the temperature–concentration extremum of the spinodal curve (as can be seen in the figure to the right).
[src:phase-transitions/ehrenfest-equations] Ehrenfest equations are the consequence of continuity of specific entropy s and specific volume v , which are first derivatives of specific Gibbs free energy – in second-order phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/ehrenfest-equations] where $i=1$ and $i=2$ are the two phases which transit one into other.
[src:phase-transitions/ehrenfest-equations] Due to continuity of specific entropy, the following holds in second-order phase transitions: ${ds_{1}}={ds_{2}}$ .
[src:phase-transitions/ehrenfest-equations] Derivatives of Gibbs free energy are not always finite.
[src:phase-transitions/ehrenfest-equations] Transitions between different magnetic states of metals can't be described by Ehrenfest equations.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Latent heat can be understood as hidden energy which is supplied or extracted to change the state of a substance without changing its temperature or pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] This includes the latent heat of fusion (solid to liquid), the latent heat of vaporization (liquid to gas) and the latent heat of sublimation (solid to gas).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The term was introduced around 1762 by Scottish chemist Joseph Black.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Black used the term in the context of calorimetry where a heat transfer caused a volume change in a body while its temperature was constant.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In contrast to latent heat, sensible heat is energy transferred as heat, with a resultant temperature change in a body.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The terms *sensible heat* and *latent heat* refer to energy transferred between a body and its surroundings, defined by the occurrence or non-occurrence of temperature change; they depend on the properties of the body.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Sensible heat is sensed or felt in a process as a change in the body's temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Latent heat is energy transferred in a process without change of the body's temperature, for example, in a phase change (solid/liquid/gas).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Both sensible and latent heats are observed in many processes of transfer of energy in nature.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The original usage of the term, as introduced by Black, was applied to systems that were intentionally held at constant temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Such usage referred to *latent heat of expansion* and several other related latent heats.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] These latent heats are defined independently of the conceptual framework of thermodynamics.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Latent heat is energy released or absorbed by a body or a thermodynamic system during a constant-temperature process.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Two common forms of latent heat are latent heat of fusion (melting) and latent heat of vaporization (boiling).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] These names describe the direction of energy flow when changing from one phase to the next: from solid to liquid, and liquid to gas.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In both cases the change is endothermic, meaning that the system absorbs energy.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] For example, when water evaporates, an input of energy is required for the water molecules to overcome the forces of attraction between them and make the transition from water to vapor.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] If the vapor then condenses to a liquid on a surface, then the vapor's latent energy absorbed during evaporation is released as the liquid's sensible heat onto the surface.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The large value of the enthalpy of condensation of water vapor is the reason that steam is a far more effective heating medium than boiling water, and is more hazardous.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In meteorology, latent heat flux is the flux of energy from the Earth's surface to the atmosphere that is associated with evaporation or transpiration of water at the surface and subsequent condensation of water vapor in the troposphere.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] It is an important component of Earth's surface energy budget.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Latent heat flux has been commonly measured with the Bowen ratio technique, or more recently since the mid-1900s by the eddy covariance method.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In 1748, an account was published in *The Edinburgh Physical and Literary Essays* of an experiment by the Scottish physician and chemist William Cullen.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Cullen had used an air pump to lower the pressure in a container with diethyl ether.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] No heat was withdrawn from the ether, yet the ether boiled, but its temperature decreased.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] And in 1758, on a warm day in Cambridge, England, Benjamin Franklin and fellow scientist John Hadley experimented by continually wetting the ball of a mercury thermometer with ether and using bellows to evaporate the ether.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] With each subsequent evaporation, the thermometer read a lower temperature, eventually reaching 7 °F (−14 °C).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Another thermometer showed that the room temperature was constant at 65 °F (18 °C).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The English word *latent* comes from Latin *latēns*, meaning *lying hidden*.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] It was known that when the air temperature rises above freezing—air then becoming the obvious heat source—snow melts very slowly and the temperature of the melted snow is close to its freezing point.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In 1757, Black started to investigate if heat, therefore, was required for the melting of a solid, independent of any rise in temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] As far as Black knew, the general view at that time was that melting was inevitably accompanied by a small increase in temperature, and that no additional heat was needed beyond what this increase in temperature would require in itself.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Soon, however, Black was able to show that much more heat was required during melting than could be explained by the increase in temperature alone.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] He was also able to show that heat is released by a liquid during its freezing; again, much more than could be explained by the decrease of its temperature alone.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Black would compare the change in temperature of two identical quantities of water, heated by identical means, one of which was, say, melted from ice, whereas the other was heated from merely cold liquid state.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Black also deduced that as much latent heat as was supplied into boiling the distillate (thus giving the quantity of fuel needed) also had to be absorbed to condense it again (thus giving the cooling water required).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In 1762, Black announced the following research and results to a society of professors at the University of Glasgow.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Black had placed equal masses of ice at 32 °F (0 °C) and water at 33 °F (0.6 °C) respectively in two identical, well separated containers.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The water and the ice were both evenly heated to 40 °F by the air in the room, which was at a constant 47 °F (8 °C).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The water had therefore received 40 – 33 = 7 “degrees of heat”.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The ice had been heated for 21 times longer and had therefore received 7 × 21 = 147 “degrees of heat”.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The temperature of the ice had increased by 8 °F.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The ice had thus absorbed 8 “degrees of heat”, which Black called *sensible heat*, manifest as a temperature increase, which could be felt and measured.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] In addition to that, 147 – 8 = 139 “degrees of heat” were absorbed as *latent heat*, manifest as phase change rather than as temperature change.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Black next showed that a water temperature of 176 °F was needed to melt an equal mass of ice until it was all 32 °F.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] So now 176 – 32 = 144 “degrees of heat” seemed to be needed to melt the ice.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The modern value for the heat of fusion of ice would be 143 “degrees of heat” on the same scale (79.5 “degrees of heat Celsius”).
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Finally, Black increased the temperature of a mass of water, then vaporized an equal mass of water by even heating.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] He showed that 830 “degrees of heat” was needed for the vaporization; again based on the time required.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The modern value for the heat of vaporization of water would be 967 “degrees of heat” on the same scale.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Later, James Prescott Joule characterised latent energy as the energy of interaction in a given configuration of particles, i.e. a form of potential energy, and the sensible heat as an energy that was indicated by the thermometer, relating the latter to thermal energy.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Intensive properties are material characteristics and are not dependent on the size or extent of the sample.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] Commonly quoted and tabulated in the literature are the specific latent heat of fusion and the specific latent heat of vaporization for many substances.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] The following table shows the specific latent heats and change of phase temperatures (at standard pressure) of some common fluids and gases.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] where the temperature T is taken to be the numerical value in °C.
[src:phase-transitions/latent-heat] As the temperature (or pressure) rises to the critical point, the latent heat of vaporization falls to zero.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In physics, chemistry and biology, a **phase transition** (or **phase change**) is the physical process of transition between one state of a medium and another.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Commonly the term is used to refer to changes among the basic states of matter: solid, liquid, and gas, and in rare cases, plasma.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A phase of a thermodynamic system and the states of matter have uniform physical properties.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] During a phase transition of a given medium, certain properties of the medium change as a result of the change of external conditions, such as temperature or pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This can be a discontinuous change; for example, a liquid may become gas upon heating to its boiling point, resulting in an abrupt change in volume.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The identification of the external conditions at which a transformation occurs defines the phase transition point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions commonly refer to when a substance transforms between one of the four states of matter to another.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] At the phase transition point for a substance, for instance the boiling point, the two phases involved - liquid and vapor, have identical free energies and therefore are equally likely to exist.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Below the boiling point, the liquid is the more stable state of the two, whereas above the boiling point the gaseous form is the more stable.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For a single component, the most stable phase at different temperatures and pressures can be shown on a phase diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Such a diagram usually depicts states in equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A phase transition usually occurs when the pressure or temperature changes and the system crosses from one region to another, like water turning from liquid to solid as soon as the temperature drops below the freezing point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In exception to the usual case, it is sometimes possible to change the state of a system diabatically (as opposed to adiabatically) in such a way that it can be brought past a phase transition point without undergoing a phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The resulting state is metastable, i.e., less stable than the phase to which the transition would have occurred, but not unstable either.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This occurs in superheating and supercooling, for example.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Metastable states do not appear on usual phase diagrams.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions can also occur when a solid changes to a different structure without changing its chemical makeup.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In elements, this is known as allotropy, whereas in compounds it is known as polymorphism.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The change from one crystal structure to another, from a crystalline solid to an amorphous solid, or from one amorphous structure to another (polyamorphs) are all examples of solid to solid phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The martensitic transformation occurs as one of the many phase transformations in carbon steel and stands as a model for displacive phase transformations.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Order-disorder transitions such as in alpha-titanium aluminides.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] As with states of matter, there is also a metastable to equilibrium phase transformation for structural phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A metastable polymorph which forms rapidly due to lower surface energy will transform to an equilibrium phase given sufficient thermal input to overcome an energetic barrier.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Many dynamic, or soft, microporous materials exhibit structural phase transitions between closed and open forms.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Metal–organic frameworks, in particular, have been extensively studied for this behavior.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The phase landscape can be more complex, with intermediate phases discovered.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Further examples show that guest molecules can stabilize specific phases, resulting in crystal configurations that depend on the composition of the surrounding atmosphere.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions can also describe the change between different kinds of magnetic ordering.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The most well-known is the transition between the ferromagnetic and paramagnetic phases of magnetic materials, which occurs at what is called the Curie point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Another example is the transition between differently ordered, commensurate or incommensurate, magnetic structures, such as in cerium antimonide.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A simplified but highly useful model of magnetic phase transitions is provided by the Ising model.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions involving solutions and mixtures are more complicated than transitions involving a single compound.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This is often the case in solid solutions, where the two components are isostructural.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] There are also a number of phase transitions involving three phases: a eutectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase liquid is cooled and transforms into two solid phases.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The same process, but beginning with a solid instead of a liquid is called a eutectoid transformation.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A peritectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase solid is heated and transforms into a solid phase and a liquid phase.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A peritectoid reaction is a peritectoid reaction, except involving only solid phases.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A monotectic reaction consists of change from a liquid and to a combination of a solid and a second liquid, where the two liquids display a miscibility gap.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Separation into multiple phases can occur via spinodal decomposition, in which a single phase is cooled and separates into two different compositions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Non-equilibrium mixtures can occur, such as in supersaturation.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions occur when the thermodynamic free energy of a system is non-analytic for some choice of thermodynamic variables (cf. phases).
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This condition generally stems from the interactions of a large number of particles in a system, and does not appear in systems that are small.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions can occur for non-thermodynamic systems, where temperature is not a parameter.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Examples include: quantum phase transitions, dynamic phase transitions, and topological (structural) phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In these types of systems other parameters take the place of temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For instance, connection probability replaces temperature for percolating networks.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Paul Ehrenfest classified phase transitions based on the behavior of the thermodynamic free energy as a function of other thermodynamic variables.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The various solid/liquid/gas transitions are classified as first-order transitions because they involve a discontinuous change in density, which is the (inverse of the) first derivative of the free energy with respect to pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] *Second-order phase transitions* are continuous in the first derivative (the order parameter, which is the first derivative of the free energy with respect to the external field, is continuous across the transition) but exhibit discontinuity in a second derivative of the free energy.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Under the Ehrenfest scheme, there could in principle be third, fourth, and higher-order phase transitions, but in practice, only first- and second-order phase transitions are generally observed.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Examples of exceptions to this include the Gross–Witten–Wadia phase transition in 2-D lattice quantum chromodynamics, which is a third-order phase transition, and the Tracy–Widom distribution, which can be interpreted as a third-order transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The Curie points of many ferromagnetics are also comsidered third-order transitions, as shown by their specific heat having a sudden change in slope.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The concept of the second-order phase transition, was for a while, controversial, as it seemed to require two "sheets" of the Gibbs free energy to osculate exactly, which was considered so unlikely as to likely never occur.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Cornelis Gorter replied the criticism, pointing out that the Gibbs free energy surface might have two sheets on one side, but only one sheet on the other side, creating a forked appearance.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The first example of a phase transition discovered that did not fit into the Ehrenfest classification was the exact solution of the Ising model, discovered in 1944 by Lars Onsager.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The exact specific heat differed from the earlier mean-field approximations, which had predicted that it has a simple discontinuity at critical temperature; instead, the exact specific heat diverged logarithmically at the critical temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In the following decades, the Ehrenfest classification was replaced by a simplified scheme that is able to incorporate such transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Related primary research reports have suggested that quenched disorder can broaden a first-order transition: that while transformation is completed over a finite range of temperatures, phenomena like supercooling and superheating survive, and hysteresis is observed on thermal cycling.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In contrast to viscosity, thermal expansion and heat capacity of amorphous materials show a relatively sudden change at the glass transition temperature, a change that enables accurate detection using differential scanning calorimetry measurements.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Several transitions are known as *infinite-order phase transitions*.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] They are continuous but break no symmetries.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The most famous example is the Kosterlitz–Thouless transition in the two-dimensional XY model.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Many quantum phase transitions, e.g., in two-dimensional electron gases, belong to this class.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Apart from isolated, simple phase transitions, there exist transition lines as well as multicritical points, when varying external parameters like the magnetic field or composition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The liquid–glass transition is observed in many polymers and other liquids that can be supercooled far below the melting point of the crystalline phase.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It is not a transition between thermodynamic ground states: it is widely believed that the true ground state is always crystalline.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Glass is a *quenched disorder* state, and its entropy, density, and so on, depend on the thermal history.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Therefore, the glass transition is primarily a dynamic phenomenon: on cooling a liquid, internal degrees of freedom successively fall out of equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Some theoretical methods predict an underlying phase transition in the hypothetical limit of infinitely long relaxation times.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] No direct experimental evidence supports the existence of these transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A disorder-broadened first-order transition occurs over a finite range of temperatures where the fraction of the low-temperature equilibrium phase grows from zero to one (100%) as the temperature is lowered.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This continuous variation of the coexisting fractions with temperature raised interesting possibilities.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] On cooling, some liquids vitrify into a glass rather than transform to the equilibrium crystal phase.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This happens if the cooling rate is faster than a critical cooling rate, and is attributed to the molecular motions becoming so slow that the molecules cannot rearrange into the crystal positions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This slowing down happens below a glass-formation temperature *T*g, which may depend on the applied pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] If the first-order freezing transition occurs over a range of temperatures, and *T*g falls within this range, then there is an interesting possibility that the transition is arrested when it is partial and incomplete.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Extending these ideas to first-order magnetic transitions being arrested at low temperatures, resulted in the observation of incomplete magnetic transitions, with two magnetic phases coexisting, down to the lowest temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] First reported in the case of a ferromagnetic to anti-ferromagnetic transition, such persistent phase coexistence has now been reported across a variety of first-order magnetic transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] These include colossal-magnetoresistance manganite materials, magnetocaloric materials, magnetic shape memory materials, and other materials.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The interesting feature of these observations of *T*g falling within the temperature range over which the transition occurs is that the first-order magnetic transition is influenced by magnetic field, just like the structural transition is influenced by pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The relative ease with which magnetic fields can be controlled, in contrast to pressure, raises the possibility that one can study the interplay between *T*g and *T*c in an exhaustive way.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase coexistence across first-order magnetic transitions will then enable the resolution of outstanding issues in understanding glasses.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In any system containing liquid and gaseous phases, there exists a special combination of pressure and temperature, known as the critical point, at which the transition between liquid and gas becomes a second-order transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Near the critical point, the fluid is sufficiently hot and compressed that the distinction between the liquid and gaseous phases is almost non-existent.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This is associated with the phenomenon of critical opalescence, a milky appearance of the liquid due to density fluctuations at all possible wavelengths (including those of visible light).
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions often involve a symmetry breaking process.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For instance, the cooling of a fluid into a crystalline solid breaks continuous translation symmetry: each point in the fluid has the same properties, but each point in a crystal does not have the same properties (unless the points are chosen from the lattice points of the crystal lattice).
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Typically, the high-temperature phase contains more symmetries than the low-temperature phase due to spontaneous symmetry breaking, with the exception of certain accidental symmetries (e.g. the formation of heavy virtual particles, which only occurs at low temperatures).
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] An **order parameter** is a measure of the degree of order across the boundaries in a phase transition system; it normally takes on the value of zero in one phase (usually above the critical point) and nonzero in the other.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] At the critical point, the order parameter susceptibility (the change of an extensive property under variation of an intensive property) will usually diverge.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] An example of an order parameter is the net magnetization in a ferromagnetic system undergoing a phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For liquid/gas transitions, the order parameter is the difference of the densities.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] From a theoretical perspective, order parameters arise from symmetry breaking.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] When this happens, one needs to introduce one or more extra variables to describe the state of the system.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For example, in the ferromagnetic phase, one must provide the net magnetization, whose direction was spontaneously chosen when the system cooled below the Curie point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] However, note that order parameters can also be defined for non-symmetry-breaking transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Some phase transitions, such as superconducting and ferromagnetic, can have order parameters for more than one degree of freedom.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In such phases, the order parameter may take the form of a complex number, a vector, or even a tensor, the magnitude of which goes to zero at the phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] There also exist dual descriptions of phase transitions in terms of disorder parameters.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] These indicate the presence of line-like excitations such as vortex- or defect lines.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Symmetry-breaking phase transitions play an important role in cosmology.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] As the universe expanded and cooled, the vacuum underwent a series of symmetry-breaking phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For example, the electroweak transition broke the SU(2)×U(1) symmetry of the electroweak field into the U(1) symmetry of the present-day electromagnetic field.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This transition is important to explain the asymmetry between the amount of matter and antimatter in the present-day universe, according to electroweak baryogenesis theory.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Progressive phase transitions in an expanding universe are implicated in the development of order in the universe, as is illustrated by the work of Eric Chaisson and David Layzer.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] See also relational order theories and order and disorder.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Continuous phase transitions are easier to study than first-order transitions due to the absence of latent heat, and they have been discovered to have many interesting properties.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The phenomena associated with continuous phase transitions are called critical phenomena, due to their association with critical points.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Continuous phase transitions can be characterized by parameters known as critical exponents.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The most important one is perhaps the exponent describing the divergence of the thermal correlation length by approaching the transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For instance, let us examine the behavior of the heat capacity near such a transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] We vary the temperature *T* of the system while keeping all the other thermodynamic variables fixed and find that the transition occurs at some critical temperature *T*c.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The heat capacity of amorphous materials has such a behaviour near the glass transition temperature where the universal critical exponent *α* = 0.59 A similar behavior, but with the exponent *ν* instead of *α*, applies for the correlation length.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The critical exponents are not necessarily the same above and below the critical temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] When a continuous symmetry is explicitly broken down to a discrete symmetry by irrelevant (in the renormalization group sense) anisotropies, then some exponents (such as $\gamma$ , the exponent of the susceptibility) are not identical.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For $\alpha <-1$ , the heat capacity remains differentiable at the transition temperature, although discontinuities appear at higher-order derivatives.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For $-1\leq \alpha <0$ , the heat capacity has a "kink" at the transition temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This is the behavior of liquid helium at the lambda transition from a normal state to the superfluid state, for which experiments have found *α* = −0.013 ± 0.003.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] At least one experiment was performed in the zero-gravity conditions of an orbiting satellite to minimize pressure differences in the sample.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This experimental value of α agrees with theoretical predictions based on variational perturbation theory.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For 0 < *α* < 1, the heat capacity diverges at the transition temperature (though, since *α* < 1, the enthalpy stays finite).
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] An example of such behavior is the 3D ferromagnetic phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In the three-dimensional Ising model for uniaxial magnets, detailed theoretical studies have yielded the exponent *α* ≈ +0.110.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Some model systems do not obey a power-law behavior.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For example, mean field theory predicts a finite discontinuity of the heat capacity at the transition temperature, and the two-dimensional Ising model has a logarithmic divergence.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] However, these systems are limiting cases and an exception to the rule.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Real phase transitions exhibit power-law behavior.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Several other critical exponents, *β*, *γ*, *δ*, *ν*, and *η*, are defined, examining the power law behavior of a measurable physical quantity near the phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It can be shown that there are only two independent exponents, e.g.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It is a remarkable fact that phase transitions arising in different systems often possess the same set of critical exponents.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This phenomenon is known as *universality*.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] For example, the critical exponents at the liquid–gas critical point have been found to be independent of the chemical composition of the fluid.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] More impressively, but understandably from above, they are an exact match for the critical exponents of the ferromagnetic phase transition in uniaxial magnets.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Such systems are said to be in the same universality class.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Again, the divergence of the correlation length is the essential point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] There are also other critical phenomena; e.g., besides *static functions* there is also *critical dynamics*.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] As a consequence, at a phase transition one may observe *critical slowing down* or *speeding up*.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Connected to the previous phenomenon is also the phenomenon of *enhanced fluctuations* before the phase transition, as a consequence of lower degree of stability of the initial phase of the system.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The large *static universality classes* of a continuous phase transition split into smaller *dynamic universality* classes.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In addition to the critical exponents, there are also universal relations for certain static or dynamic functions of the magnetic fields and temperature differences from the critical value.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A variety of methods are applied for studying the various effects.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions play many important roles in biological systems.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In *biological membranes*, gel to liquid crystalline phase transitions play a critical role in physiological functioning of biomembranes.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In gel phase, due to low fluidity of membrane lipid fatty-acyl chains, membrane proteins have restricted movement and thus are restrained in exercise of their physiological role.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Plants depend critically on photosynthesis by chloroplast thylakoid membranes which are exposed cold environmental temperatures.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Thylakoid membranes retain innate fluidity even at relatively low temperatures because of high degree of fatty-acyl disorder allowed by their high content of linolenic acid, 18-carbon chain with 3-double bonds.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Gel-to-liquid crystalline phase transition temperature of biological membranes can be determined by many techniques including calorimetry, fluorescence, spin label electron paramagnetic resonance and NMR by recording measurements of the concerned parameter by at series of sample temperatures.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A simple method for its determination from 13-C NMR line intensities has also been proposed.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It has been proposed that some biological systems might lie near critical points.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Examples include neural networks in the salamander retina, bird flocks, gene expression networks in Drosophila, and protein folding.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] However, it is not clear whether or not alternative reasons could explain some of the phenomena supporting arguments for criticality.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It has also been suggested that biological organisms share two key properties of phase transitions: the change of macroscopic behavior and the coherence of a system at a critical point.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions are prominent feature of motor behavior in biological systems.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Spontaneous gait transitions, as well as fatigue-induced motor task disengagements, show typical critical behavior as an intimation of the sudden qualitative change of the previously stable motor behavioral pattern.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The characteristic feature of second order phase transitions is the appearance of fractals in some scale-free properties.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] It has long been known that protein globules are shaped by interactions with water.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] There are 20 amino acids that form side groups on protein peptide chains range from hydrophilic to hydrophobic, causing the former to lie near the globular surface, while the latter lie closer to the globular center.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Twenty fractals were discovered in solvent associated surface areas of > 5000 protein segments.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] The existence of these fractals proves that proteins function near critical points of second-order phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] In groups of organisms in stress (when approaching critical transitions), correlations tend to increase, while at the same time, fluctuations also increase.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] This effect is supported by many experiments and observations of groups of people, mice, trees, and grassy plants.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] Phase transitions have been hypothesised to occur in social systems viewed as dynamical systems.
[src:phase-transitions/order-parameter] A hypothesis proposed in the 1990s and 2000s in the context of peace and armed conflict is that when a conflict that is non-violent shifts to a phase of armed conflict, this is a phase transition from latent to manifest phases within the dynamical system.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A **phase diagram** in physical chemistry, engineering, mineralogy, and materials science is a type of chart used to show conditions (pressure, temperature, etc.) at which thermodynamically distinct phases (such as solid, liquid or gaseous states) occur and coexist at equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Common components of a phase diagram are *lines of equilibrium* or *phase boundaries*, which refer to lines that mark conditions under which multiple phases can coexist at equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Phase transitions occur along lines of equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Metastable phases are not shown in phase diagrams as, despite their common occurrence, they are not equilibrium phases.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Triple points are points on phase diagrams where lines of equilibrium intersect.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Triple points mark conditions at which three different phases can coexist.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For example, the water phase diagram has a triple point corresponding to the single temperature and pressure at which solid, liquid, and gaseous water can coexist in a stable equilibrium (273.16 K and a partial vapor pressure of 611.657 Pa).
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The pressure on a pressure-temperature diagram (such as the water phase diagram shown) is that of the substance in question (e.g., the environmental pressure for a condensed state and the partial pressure for the gas state).
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The solidus is the temperature below which the substance is stable in the solid state.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The liquidus is the temperature above which the substance is stable in a liquid state.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] There may be a gap between the solidus and liquidus; within the gap, the substance consists of a mixture of crystals and liquid (like a "slurry").
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Working fluids are often categorized on the basis of the shape of their phase diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The simplest phase diagrams are pressure–temperature diagrams of a single simple substance, such as water.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The axes correspond to the pressure and temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The phase diagram shows, in pressure–temperature space, the lines of equilibrium or phase boundaries between the three phases of solid, liquid, and gas.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The curves on the phase diagram show the points where the free energy (and other derived properties) becomes non-analytic: their derivatives with respect to the coordinates (temperature and pressure in this example) change discontinuously (abruptly).
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For example, the heat capacity of a container filled with ice will change abruptly as the container is heated past the melting point.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The open spaces, where the free energy is analytic, correspond to single phase regions.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Single phase regions are separated by lines of non-analytical behavior, where phase transitions occur, which are called **phase boundaries**.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] In the diagram on the right, the phase boundary between liquid and gas does not continue indefinitely.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Instead, it terminates at a point on the phase diagram called the critical point.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] This reflects the fact that, at extremely high temperatures and pressures, the liquid and gaseous phases become indistinguishable, in what is known as a supercritical fluid.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The existence of the liquid–gas critical point reveals a slight ambiguity in labelling the single phase regions.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] When going from the liquid to the gaseous phase, one usually crosses the phase boundary, but it is possible to choose a path that never crosses the boundary by going to the right of the critical point.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Thus, the liquid and gaseous phases can blend continuously into each other.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The solid–liquid phase boundary can only end in a critical point if the solid and liquid phases have the same symmetry group.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For most substances, the solid–liquid phase boundary (or fusion curve) in the phase diagram has a positive slope so that the melting point increases with pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] This is true whenever the solid phase is denser than the liquid phase.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The greater the pressure on a given substance, the closer together the molecules of the substance are brought to each other, which increases the effect of the substance's intermolecular forces.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Thus, the substance requires a higher temperature for its molecules to have enough energy to break out of the fixed pattern of the solid phase and enter the liquid phase.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A similar concept applies to liquid–gas phase changes.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Water is an exception which has a solid-liquid boundary with negative slope so that the melting point decreases with pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] This occurs because ice (solid water) is less dense than liquid water, as shown by the fact that ice floats on water.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] At a molecular level, ice is less dense because it has a more extensive network of hydrogen bonding which requires a greater separation of water molecules.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Other exceptions include antimony and bismuth.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] At very high pressures above 50 GPa (500 000 atm), liquid nitrogen undergoes a liquid-liquid phase transition to a polymeric form and becomes denser than solid nitrogen at the same pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Under these conditions therefore, solid nitrogen also floats in its liquid.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] where Δ*H*fus is the heat of fusion which is always positive, and Δ*V*fus is the volume change for fusion.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For most substances Δ*V*fus is positive so that the slope is positive.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] However for water and other exceptions, Δ*V*fus is negative so that the slope is negative.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] In addition to temperature and pressure, other thermodynamic properties may be graphed in phase diagrams.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Examples of such thermodynamic properties include specific volume, specific enthalpy, or specific entropy.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For example, single-component graphs of temperature vs. specific entropy (*T* vs.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] *s*) for water/steam or for a refrigerant are commonly used to illustrate thermodynamic cycles such as a Carnot cycle, Rankine cycle, or vapor-compression refrigeration cycle.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Any two thermodynamic quantities may be shown on the horizontal and vertical axes of a two-dimensional diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Additional thermodynamic quantities may each be illustrated in increments as a series of lines—curved, straight, or a combination of curved and straight.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Each of these **iso-**lines represents the thermodynamic quantity at a certain constant value.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] It is possible to envision three-dimensional (3D) graphs showing three thermodynamic quantities.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For example, for a single component, a 3D Cartesian coordinate type graph can show temperature (*T*) on one axis, pressure (*p*) on a second axis, and specific volume (*v*) on a third.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Such a 3D graph is sometimes called a *p*–*v*–*T* diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The equilibrium conditions are shown as curves on a curved surface in 3D with areas for solid, liquid, and vapor phases and areas where solid and liquid, solid and vapor, or liquid and vapor coexist in equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A line on the surface called a **triple line** is where solid, liquid and vapor can all coexist in equilibrium.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The critical point remains a point on the surface even on a 3D phase diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] An orthographic projection of the 3D *p*–*v*–*T* graph showing pressure and temperature as the vertical and horizontal axes collapses the 3D plot into the standard 2D pressure–temperature diagram.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] When this is done, the solid–vapor, solid–liquid, and liquid–vapor surfaces collapse into three corresponding curved lines meeting at the triple point, which is the collapsed orthographic projection of the triple line.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Other much more complex types of phase diagrams can be constructed, particularly when more than one pure component is present.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] In that case, concentration becomes an important variable.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams with more than two dimensions can be constructed that show the effect of more than two variables on the phase of a substance.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams can use other variables in addition to or in place of temperature, pressure and composition, for example the strength of an applied electrical or magnetic field, and they can also involve substances that take on more than just three states of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] One type of phase diagram plots temperature against the relative concentrations of two substances in a binary mixture called a *binary phase diagram*, as shown at right.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Such a mixture can be either a solid solution, eutectic or peritectic, among others.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] These two types of mixtures result in very different graphs.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Another type of binary phase diagram is a *boiling-point diagram* for a mixture of two components, i. e. chemical compounds.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For two particular volatile components at a certain pressure such as atmospheric pressure, a boiling-point diagram shows what vapor (gas) compositions are in equilibrium with given liquid compositions depending on temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] In a typical binary boiling-point diagram, temperature is plotted on a vertical axis and mixture composition on a horizontal axis.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A two component diagram with components A and B in an "ideal" solution is shown.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The construction of a liquid vapor phase diagram assumes an ideal liquid solution obeying Raoult's law and an ideal gas mixture obeying Dalton's law of partial pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A tie line from the liquid to the gas at constant pressure would indicate the two compositions of the liquid and gas respectively.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A simple example diagram with hypothetical components 1 and 2 in a non-azeotropic mixture is shown at right.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The fact that there are two separate curved lines joining the boiling points of the pure components means that the vapor composition is usually not the same as the liquid composition the vapor is in equilibrium with.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] See Vapor–liquid equilibrium for more information.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] In addition to the above-mentioned types of phase diagrams, there are many other possible combinations.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Some of the major features of phase diagrams include congruent points, where a solid phase transforms directly into a liquid.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] There is also the peritectoid, a point where two solid phases combine into one solid phase during cooling.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The inverse of this, when one solid phase transforms into two solid phases during cooling, is called the eutectoid.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A complex phase diagram of great technological importance is that of the iron–carbon system for less than 7% carbon (see steel).
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The x-axis of such a diagram represents the concentration variable of the mixture.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] As the mixtures are typically far from dilute and their density as a function of temperature is usually unknown, the preferred concentration measure is mole fraction.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A volume-based measure like molarity would be inadvisable.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] A system with three components is called a ternary system.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] At constant pressure the maximum number of independent variables is three – the temperature and two concentration values.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] For a representation of ternary equilibria a three-dimensional phase diagram is required.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Often such a diagram is drawn with the composition as a horizontal plane and the temperature on an axis perpendicular to this plane.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] To represent composition in a ternary system an equilateral triangle is used, called Gibbs triangle (see also Ternary plot).
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The temperature scale is plotted on the axis perpendicular to the composition triangle.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Thus, the space model of a ternary phase diagram is a right-triangular prism.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] The prism sides represent corresponding binary systems A-B, B-C, A-C.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] However, the most common methods to present phase equilibria in a ternary system are the following: 1) projections on the concentration triangle ABC of the liquidus, solidus, solvus surfaces; 2) isothermal sections; 3) vertical sections.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Polymorphic and polyamorphic substances have multiple crystal or amorphous phases, which can be graphed in a similar fashion to solid, liquid, and gas phases.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Some organic materials pass through intermediate states between solid and liquid; these states are called mesophases.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Attention has been directed to mesophases because they enable display devices and have become commercially important through the so-called liquid-crystal technology.
[src:phase-transitions/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams are used to describe the occurrence of mesophases.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In physics, a **state of matter** or **phase of matter** is one of the distinct forms in which matter can exist.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Four states of matter are observable in everyday life: solid, liquid, gas, and plasma.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Different states are distinguished by the ways the component particles (atoms, molecules, ions and electrons) are arranged, and how they behave collectively.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a solid, the particles are tightly packed and held in fixed positions, giving the material a definite shape and volume.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a liquid, the particles remain close together but can move past one another, allowing the substance to maintain a fixed volume while adapting to the shape of its container.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a gas, the particles are far apart and move freely, allowing the substance to expand and fill both the shape and volume of its container.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Plasma is similar to a gas, but it also contains charged particles (ions and free electrons) that move independently and respond to electric and magnetic fields.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Beyond the classical states of matter, a wide variety of additional states are known to exist.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Some of these lie between the traditional categories; for example, liquid crystals exhibit properties of both solids and liquids.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Others represent entirely different kinds of ordering.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Magnetic states, for instance, do not depend on the spatial arrangement of atoms, but rather on the alignment of their intrinsic magnetic moments (spins).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Even in a solid where atoms are fixed in position, the spins can organize in distinct ways, giving rise to magnetic states such as ferromagnetism or antiferromagnetism.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Some states occur only under extreme conditions, such as Bose–Einstein condensates and Fermionic condensates (in extreme cold), neutron-degenerate matter (in extreme density), and quark–gluon plasma (at extremely high energy).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The term *phase* is sometimes used as a synonym for state of matter, but it is possible for a single compound to form different phases that are in the same state of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] For example, ice is the solid state of water, but there are multiple phases of ice with different crystal structures, which are formed at different pressures and temperatures.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a solid, constituent particles (ions, atoms, or molecules) are closely packed together.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The forces between particles are so strong that the particles cannot move freely but can only vibrate.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] As a result, a solid has a stable, definite shape, and a definite volume.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Solids can only change their shape by an outside force, as when broken or cut.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In crystalline solids, the particles (atoms, molecules, or ions) are packed in a regularly ordered, repeating pattern.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] There are various different crystal structures, and the same substance can have more than one structure (or solid phase).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] For example, iron has a body-centred cubic structure at temperatures below 912 °C (1,674 °F), and a face-centred cubic structure between 912 and 1,394 °C (2,541 °F).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Ice has fifteen known crystal structures, or fifteen solid phases, which exist at various temperatures and pressures.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Glasses and other non-crystalline, amorphous solids without long-range order are not thermal equilibrium ground states; therefore they are described below as nonclassical states of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Solids can be transformed into liquids by melting, and liquids can be transformed into solids by freezing.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Solids can also change directly into gases through the process of sublimation, and gases can likewise change directly into solids through deposition.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A liquid is a nearly incompressible fluid that conforms to the shape of its container but retains a (nearly) constant volume independent of pressure.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The volume is definite if the temperature and pressure are constant.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] When a solid is heated above its melting point, it becomes liquid, given that the pressure is higher than the triple point of the substance.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Intermolecular (or interatomic or interionic) forces are still important, but the molecules have enough energy to move relative to each other and the structure is mobile.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This means that the shape of a liquid is not definite but is determined by its container.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The volume is usually greater than that of the corresponding solid, the best known exception being water, H2O.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The highest temperature at which a given liquid can exist is its critical temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Not only will a gas conform to the shape of its container but it will also expand to fill the container.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a gas, the molecules have enough kinetic energy so that the effect of intermolecular forces is small (or zero for an ideal gas), and the typical distance between neighboring molecules is much greater than the molecular size.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A gas has no definite shape or volume, but occupies the entire container in which it is confined.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A liquid may be converted to a gas by heating at constant pressure to the boiling point, or else by reducing the pressure at constant temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At temperatures below its critical temperature, a gas is also called a vapor, and can be liquefied by compression alone without cooling.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A vapor can exist in equilibrium with a liquid (or solid), in which case the gas pressure equals the vapor pressure of the liquid (or solid).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A supercritical fluid (SCF) is a gas whose temperature and pressure are above the critical temperature and critical pressure respectively.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In this state, the distinction between liquid and gas disappears.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A supercritical fluid has the physical properties of a gas, but its high density confers solvent properties in some cases, which leads to useful applications.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] For example, supercritical carbon dioxide is used to extract caffeine in the manufacture of decaffeinated coffee.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A gas is usually converted to a plasma in one of two ways, either from a huge voltage difference between two points, or by exposing it to extremely high temperatures.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Heating matter to high temperatures causes electrons to leave the atoms, resulting in the presence of free electrons.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This creates a so-called partially ionized plasma.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At very high temperatures, such as those present in stars, it is assumed that essentially all electrons are "free", and that a very high-energy plasma is essentially bare nuclei swimming in a sea of electrons.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This forms the so-called fully ionized plasma.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The plasma state is often misunderstood, and although not freely existing under normal conditions on Earth, it is quite commonly generated by either lightning, electric sparks, fluorescent lights, neon lights or in plasma televisions.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The Sun's corona, some types of flame, and stars are all examples of illuminated matter in the plasma state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Plasma is by far the most abundant of the four fundamental states; 99% of all ordinary matter in the universe is plasma, as it composes all stars.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A state of matter is also characterized by phase transitions.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A phase transition indicates a change in structure and can be recognized by an abrupt change in properties.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A distinct state of matter can be defined as any set of states distinguished from any other set of states by a phase transition.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Water can be said to have several distinct solid states.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The appearance of superconductivity is associated with a phase transition, so there are superconductive states.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Likewise, ferromagnetic states are demarcated by phase transitions and have distinctive properties.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] When the change of state occurs in stages the intermediate steps are called mesophases.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Such phases have been exploited by the introduction of liquid crystal technology.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The state or *phase* of a given set of matter can change depending on pressure and temperature conditions, transitioning to other phases as these conditions change to favor their existence; for example, solid transitions to liquid with an increase in temperature.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Near absolute zero, a substance exists as a solid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] As heat is added to this substance it melts into a liquid at its melting point, boils into a gas at its boiling point, and if heated high enough would enter a plasma state in which the electrons are so energized that they leave their parent atoms.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Forms of matter that are not composed of molecules and are organized by different forces can also be considered different states of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Superfluids (like Fermionic condensate) and the quark–gluon plasma are examples.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Schematic representation of a random-network glassy form (left) and ordered crystalline lattice (right) of identical chemical composition.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Glass is a non-crystalline or amorphous solid material that exhibits a glass transition when heated towards the liquid state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Glasses can be made of quite different classes of materials: inorganic networks (such as window glass, made of silicate plus additives), metallic alloys, ionic melts, aqueous solutions, molecular liquids, and polymers.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Thermodynamically, a glass is in a metastable state with respect to its crystalline counterpart.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The conversion rate, however, is practically zero.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A plastic crystal is a molecular solid with long-range positional order but with constituent molecules retaining rotational freedom; in an orientational glass this degree of freedom is frozen in a quenched disordered state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Similarly, in a spin glass magnetic disorder is frozen.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Liquid crystal states have properties intermediate between mobile liquids and ordered solids.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Generally, they are able to flow like a liquid but exhibit long-range order.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] For example, the nematic phase consists of long rod-like molecules such as para-azoxyanisole, which is nematic in the temperature range 118–136 °C (244–277 °F).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In this state the molecules flow as in a liquid, but they all point in the same direction (within each domain) and cannot rotate freely.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Like a crystalline solid, but unlike a liquid, liquid crystals react to polarized light.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Other types of liquid crystals are described in the main article on these states.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Several types have technological importance, for example, in liquid crystal displays.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Copolymers can undergo microphase separation to form a diverse array of periodic nanostructures, as shown in the example of the styrene-butadiene-styrene block copolymer shown at right.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Microphase separation can be understood by analogy to the phase separation between oil and water.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Due to chemical incompatibility between the blocks, block copolymers undergo a similar phase separation.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] However, because the blocks are covalently bonded to each other, they cannot demix macroscopically as water and oil can, and so instead the blocks form nanometre-sized structures.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Depending on the relative lengths of each block and the overall block topology of the polymer, many morphologies can be obtained, each its own phase of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Ionic liquids also display microphase separation.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The anion and cation are not necessarily compatible and would demix otherwise, but electric charge attraction prevents them from separating.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Their anions and cations appear to diffuse within compartmentalized layers or micelles instead of freely as in a uniform liquid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Transition metal atoms often have magnetic moments due to the net spin of electrons that remain unpaired and do not form chemical bonds.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In some solids the magnetic moments on different atoms are ordered and can form a ferromagnet, an antiferromagnet or a ferrimagnet.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a ferromagnet—for instance, solid iron—the magnetic moment on each atom is aligned in the same direction (within a magnetic domain).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] If the domains are also aligned, the solid is a permanent magnet, which is magnetic even in the absence of an external magnetic field.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The magnetization disappears when the magnet is heated to the Curie point, which for iron is 768 °C (1,414 °F).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] An antiferromagnet has two networks of equal and opposite magnetic moments, which cancel each other out so that the net magnetization is zero.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] For example, in nickel(II) oxide (NiO), half the nickel atoms have moments aligned in one direction and half in the opposite direction.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a ferrimagnet, the two networks of magnetic moments are opposite but unequal, so that cancellation is incomplete and there is a non-zero net magnetization.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] An example is magnetite (Fe3O4), which contains Fe2+ and Fe3+ ions with different magnetic moments.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A quantum spin liquid (QSL) is a disordered state in a system of interacting quantum spins which preserves its disorder to very low temperatures, unlike other disordered states.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] It is not a liquid in physical sense, but a solid whose magnetic order is inherently disordered.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The name "liquid" is due to an analogy with the molecular disorder in a conventional liquid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A QSL is neither a ferromagnet, where magnetic domains are parallel, nor an antiferromagnet, where the magnetic domains are antiparallel; instead, the magnetic domains are randomly oriented.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This can be realized e.g. by geometrically frustrated magnetic moments that cannot point uniformly parallel or antiparallel.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] When cooling down and settling to a state, the domain must "choose" an orientation, but if the possible states are similar in energy, one will be chosen randomly.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Consequently, despite strong short-range order, there is no long-range magnetic order.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Bose–Einstein condensation was predicted in 1925 by Albert Einstein, based on the particle statistics developed by him and Satyendra Nath Bose.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Bose-Einstein condensation occurs when bosonic particles are cooled close to absolute zero, −273.15 °C (−459.67 °F).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At a specific temperature, a large fraction of them suddenly occupies the same lowest energy quantum state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The effect is termed *condensation* in analogy with the condensation of water, with which it shares some similarities.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In 1937, it was discovered that helium-4, the most common isotope of helium, forms a superfluid below the lambda temperature of 2.17 K (−270.98 °C; −455.76 °F).
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The state is described as *superfluid* because it has zero viscosity and flows without friction.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In this state it will attempt to "climb" out of its container.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] It also has infinite thermal conductivity so that no temperature gradient can form in a superfluid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Placing a superfluid in a spinning container will result in quantized vortices.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] These properties are explained by the theory that helium-4 atoms form a Bose–Einstein condensate in the superfluid state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In the gas phase, the Bose–Einstein condensate remained an unverified theoretical prediction for many years.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] However in 1995, the research groups of Eric Cornell and Carl Wieman, of JILA at the University of Colorado at Boulder, produced the first such condensate experimentally with rubidium atoms.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Independently of Cornell and Wieman, Wolfgang Ketterle also produced a Bose–Einstein condensate in a gas of sodium atoms in 1995.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A *fermionic condensate* is similar to the Bose–Einstein condensate but composed of fermions.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] While the Pauli exclusion principle prevents individual fermions from occupying the same quantum state, pairs of fermions can combine to form composite particles that behave like bosons.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] These pairs can then occupy the same state, forming a condensate analogous to a Bose–Einstein condensate.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Examples of fermionic condensates include superconductors and the superfluid phase of helium-3, a rare isotope of helium.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Fermionic condensate has also been observed in ultracold lithium-6.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Superconductors are materials which have zero electrical resistivity, and therefore perfect conductivity.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This is a distinct physical state which exists at low temperature, and the resistivity increases discontinuously to a finite value at a sharply defined transition temperature for each superconductor.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A superconductor also excludes all magnetic fields from its interior, a phenomenon known as the Meissner effect or perfect diamagnetism.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Superconducting magnets are used as electromagnets in magnetic resonance imaging machines.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The phenomenon of superconductivity was discovered in 1911, and for 75 years was only known in some metals and metallic alloys at temperatures below 30 K.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In 1986 so-called high-temperature superconductivity was discovered in certain ceramic oxides, and has now been observed in temperatures as high as 164 K.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Under extremely high pressure, as in the cores of dead stars, ordinary matter undergoes a transition to a series of exotic states of matter collectively known as degenerate matter, which are supported mainly by quantum mechanical effects.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In physics, "degenerate" refers to two states that have the same energy and are thus interchangeable.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Degenerate matter is supported by the Pauli exclusion principle, which prevents two fermionic particles from occupying the same quantum state.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Unlike regular plasma, degenerate plasma expands little when heated, because there are simply no momentum states left.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Consequently, degenerate stars collapse into very high densities.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] More massive degenerate stars are smaller, because the gravitational force increases, but pressure does not increase proportionally.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Electron-degenerate matter is found inside white dwarf stars.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Electrons remain bound to atoms but are able to transfer to adjacent atoms.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Neutron-degenerate matter is found in neutron stars.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Vast gravitational pressure compresses atoms so strongly that the electrons are forced to combine with protons via inverse beta-decay, resulting in a superdense conglomeration of neutrons.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Normally free neutrons outside an atomic nucleus will decay with a half life of approximately 10 minutes, but in a neutron star, the decay is overtaken by inverse decay.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Cold degenerate matter is also present in planets such as Jupiter and in the even more massive brown dwarfs, which are expected to have a core with metallic hydrogen.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Because of the degeneracy, more massive brown dwarfs are not significantly larger.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In metals, the electrons can be modeled as a degenerate gas moving in a lattice of non-degenerate positive ions.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In regular cold matter, quarks, fundamental particles of nuclear matter, are confined by the strong force into hadrons that consist of 2–4 quarks, such as protons and neutrons.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Quark matter or quantum chromodynamical (QCD) matter is a group of phases where the strong force is overcome and quarks are deconfined and free to move.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Quark matter phases occur at extremely high densities or temperatures, and there are no known ways to produce them in equilibrium in the laboratory; in ordinary conditions, any quark matter formed immediately undergoes radioactive decay.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Strange matter is a type of quark matter that is suspected to exist inside some neutron stars close to the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit (approximately 2–3 solar masses), although there is no direct evidence of its existence.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In strange matter, part of the energy available manifests as strange quarks, a heavier analogue of the common down quark.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] It may be stable at lower energy states once formed, although this is not known.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Quark–gluon plasma is a very high-temperature phase in which quarks become free and able to move independently, rather than being perpetually bound into particles, in a sea of gluons, subatomic particles that transmit the strong force that binds quarks together.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This is analogous to the liberation of electrons from atoms in a plasma.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This state is briefly attainable in extremely high-energy heavy ion collisions in particle accelerators, and allows scientists to observe the properties of individual quarks.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Theories predicting the existence of quark–gluon plasma were developed in the late 1970s and early 1980s, and it was detected for the first time in the laboratory at CERN in the year 2000.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Unlike plasma, which flows like a gas, interactions within QGP are strong and it flows like a liquid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At high densities but relatively low temperatures, quarks are theorized to form a quark liquid whose nature is presently unknown.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] It forms a distinct color-flavor locked (CFL) phase at even higher densities.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This phase is superconductive for color charge.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] These phases may occur in neutron stars but they are presently theoretical.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Color-glass condensate is a type of matter theorized to exist in atomic nuclei traveling near the speed of light.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] According to Einstein's theory of relativity, a high-energy nucleus appears length contracted, or compressed, along its direction of motion.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] As a result, the gluons inside the nucleus appear to a stationary observer as a "gluonic wall" traveling near the speed of light.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At very high energies, the density of the gluons in this wall is seen to increase greatly.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Various theories predict new states of matter at very high energies.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] An unknown state has created the baryon asymmetry in the universe, but little is known about it.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In string theory, a Hagedorn temperature is predicted for superstrings at about 1030 K, where superstrings are copiously produced.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] At the Planck temperature (1032 K), gravity becomes a significant force between individual particles.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] No current theory can describe these states and they cannot be produced with any foreseeable experiment.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] However, these states are important in cosmology because the universe may have passed through these states in the Big Bang.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A supersolid is a spatially ordered material (that is, a solid or crystal) with superfluid properties.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Similar to a superfluid, a supersolid is able to move without friction but retains a rigid shape.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Although a supersolid is a solid, it exhibits so many characteristic properties different from other solids that many argue it is another state of matter.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a string-net liquid, atoms have apparently unstable arrangement, like a liquid, but are still consistent in overall pattern, like a solid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] When in a normal solid state, the atoms of matter align themselves in a grid pattern, so that the spin of any electron is the opposite of the spin of all electrons touching it.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] But in a string-net liquid, atoms are arranged in some pattern that requires some electrons to have neighbors with the same spin.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This gives rise to curious properties, as well as supporting some unusual proposals about the fundamental conditions of the universe itself.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A superglass is a phase of matter characterized, at the same time, by superfluidity and a frozen amorphous structure.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Metals, like potassium, in the chain-melted state appear to behave as liquids and solids at the same time.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This is a result of being subjected to high temperature and pressure, leading the chains in the potassium to dissolve into a liquid while the crystals remain solid.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A *quantum Hall state* gives rise to quantized Hall voltage measured in the direction perpendicular to the current flow.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] A *quantum spin Hall state* is a theoretical phase that may pave the way for the development of electronic devices that dissipate less energy and generate less heat.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] Photonic matter is a phenomenon where photons interacting with a gas develop apparent mass, and can interact with each other, even forming photonic "molecules".
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] The source of mass is the gas, which is massive.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] This is in contrast to photons moving in empty space, which have no rest mass, and cannot interact.
[src:phase-transitions/state-of-matter] In a chemical equation, the state of matter of the chemicals may be shown as (s) for solid, (l) for liquid, and (g) for gas.
